snippet.textDisplay:
I am with having rules on immigration that apply to all, and if Novak Djokovic didn’t have the documents to back up his exemption and visa application then he cannot enter. I also think that his stance on vaccinations is shameful, and that the comments by his family and some of his countrymen are grotesquely over the top and don’t serve them well.

At the same time, I do not understand why the Australian authorities treat him like this - move him to a cheap hotel that is used for illegal immigrants without a place to stay, instead of allowing him to quarantine in the place he rented while he is waiting for his court date, for example. With this, Australia makes itself look bad, and generates the impression that it uses the Djokovic case for political games. I thought that Nick Kyrgios said it well: Djokovic is still a great champion of the sport and a human, and deserves decent treatment - whatever the immigration case against him. This treatment is not decent.

Overall, in this affair nobody looks good. All it does is produce tons of bad blood that didn’t need to be produced.

snippet.textDisplay: What a lot of BS about nothing. It is a visa requirement to be vaccinated to enter Australia. As an Australian citizen I think this is very sensible, as do the majority of Australians. We have around 95% of our population vaccinated if you want to come here then you need to be vaccinated. There is no embarrassment, we are not embarrassed. Serbia has had over 12,000 deaths from COVID, Australia has had fewer than 2,500 despite having a population 25 times bigger than Serbia. I'm quite comfortable with a government that doesn't Panter to the tin foil hat wearing "freedom" brigade. We have rules in Australia to protect the elderly, those with pre existing health condition s and the immune compromised. Not to mention the health care system. That's who we are, if other nations want to throw those people and their healthcare system under a bus that's there choice.
